question: What are the specific technical elective courses offered in the MEng in AI program? Can students specialize in areas like computer vision, natural language processing, or reinforcement learning?
output: In the Fall semester of the MEng in AI program, students take AIPI.503: Deep Learning for AI, which covers many of the core techniques used in computer vision, natural language processing, and reinforcement learning. In the Spring semester, students take AIPI.513: Advanced Topics in AI, which offers a deeper dive into specific topics such as computer vision, natural language processing, and reinforcement learning. question: Does the program offer any opportunities to take courses from other Duke engineering or computer science graduate programs as part of the electives?
output:
Yes, students may take courses outside of Pratt as long as the topic is related to their area of study and with permission from both the instructor and the student's home program. Please note that AIPI students take a fixed set of courses during the Fall semester, so it is unlikely that there will be many opportunities for AIPI students to take courses outside of Pratt during the Fall semester.

question: Are there any capstone project options that allow students to work on real-world AI applications with industry partners?
output:
Yes, AIPI students have the opportunity to participate in capstone projects that are sponsored by industry partners and are focused on solving real-world problems using AI and machine learning. These projects are taken in small groups of 2-3 students and are a great way for students to apply the skills they learn in the AIPI program to practical, industry problems.

question: What types of jobs and companies do graduates of the MEng in AI program typically go on to work for?
output:
Our graduates have gone on to work in a wide variety of roles at companies including Amazon, Apple, Facebook, Google, Microsoft, Palantir, and Uber, as well as many startups. Common roles for our graduates include machine learning engineer, data scientist, research scientist, and software engineer.
